The European Parliament must give consent to the Council to conclude the trade agreement. 'Next year, the Council will adopt the decision on the conclusion of the EU-UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement, once the European Parliament has given its consent and once all procedures necessary for the entry into force have been completed, according to the release.' It would seem that the consent is provisional at this time. Some part of the EU (such as Wallonia have done before) or Macron under pressure from Fishermen, could delay the conclusion. Therefore the 'conclusion' as specified in the question will not happen before 1st January 2021.

Lesson not to engage with questions that have a high process fetish ... especially when such processes are not entwined with the main outcome. Nobody in real world cares about pedantic/ non-essential processes. I heard alot is UK and EU going to do a trade deal ... I have generally got hosed on Brexit questions and it looks like this is going to be no exception. Why am I not at 100%? If I have read the procedures right, basically UK parliament needs to agree, EU Council formally agree, then this is implemented and signed and comes into temporary force, simultaneously the request will got to the EU parliament. That request and the agreement going into force seem to be simultaneous. With the confusion from even 1 day of WTO terms could bring, it seems everyone is motivated to meet it. Seems very unlikely (maybe 1 or 2 percent) that either UK parliament or EU council will turn this down. Opposition in the UK have essentially said they will approve it and while with 27 national government sign offs needed, you would think there is some risk of an issue, everyone has said the negotiating teams have kept everyone informed. However, the time line is very tight. UK parliament set to approve on 30th December. Not clear when EU Governments are approving and that seems to be an ‚Äúemail‚Äù type process, although there was some discussion the Swedish parliament needs to approve it at one point (cannot find anything now). So we have a situation where the earliest point for this to be resolved positively is probably late on 30th.

The European Parliament has said it does not have time to discuss and vote on ratifying such an agreement before the transition period expires on December 31. This means the deal will be ‚Äúprovisionally applied‚Äù until MEPs get to vote on it in January. ^https://www.itv.com/news/2020-12-24/a-brexit-deal-has-been-done-this-is-what-happens-next

I have to say this has been the most difficult question to date, with deadline extensions, threats from both sides, and now tempered talk of compromise with one final push. Every deadline was crucial, and a no deal would happen after each, but then a new crucial deadline was made. All signs pointed to the EU Parliament not approving a deal this year after Sunday because they wouldn't have enough time, but now they will still have time if they reach an agreement today, but they don't have enough time so they may implement the deal provisionally. If they do come to an agreement, it will be sent to Parliament fast, officially resolving the question, but will they get there in the next few days? I think they are going to come to an acceptable agreement on all sides and the current UK talk of preparing for a no deal is just Johnson's way of trying to get the EU to cave a bit. It looks like both sides have made compromises, with the UK reducing its fishing demand from 60% reduction to 35% reduction over 3 years. The EU was asking for 25% over 6 years, so there is still a gap, but manageable. The EU also may have given in a bit on the level playing field talks, allowing for the UK to have more control over its sovereignty without immediate push back or tariffs if the UK does not follow new EU trade laws. It allows for other options other than automatic retaliation. I don't know how this one will go, but with as much as there is at stake, and the recent concessions, I believe they will get there.

This issue has become an emotive and political argument rather than pragmatic business- based rules. If Boris Johnson gives any ground to the detriment of UK sovereignty (perceived) he will be finished as the Prime Minister by his backbenchers of the conservative party and the influential ERG. France has taken the protection of the EU as a personal matter, as their baby. It would appear that Macron will lose all access to the North Sea fishing grounds as a matter of principle as well as sacrificing the German automotive and the Italian wine industry in their lucrative UK businesses. The latest EU demands concern the adherence of the UK of future laws embraced by the EU with governance by the EU courts, that ignores any recognition of sovereignty. France cannot allow the UK to be a successful entity outside the Single market as it might influence others, such as Sweden and Italy (which are both significant economies). There has much made of the UK of 1 being against the other 27 countries. However, the countries who will be severely affected by a separation of the market is only Belgium, Italy, France, Netherlands, Germany and obviously Eire. The UK, being the 6th largest economy in the world creates a large hole in the EU single market as an entity in the global market. The whole process of the UK leaving the EU single market bloc has been made difficult by the segments of the establishment to delay and stop the separation of the UK from the EU project. The major question is one of sovereignty over potential trade opportunities, remembering that the Conservative party gained an 80-seat majority in Government by gaining seats in the north of England by the promise of offering the deliverance of Brexit in line with the 2016 referendum. The percentage concerning the answer to this question could be 90/10 or 10/90 and therefore 50/50 is the only sensible forecast which will probably prove to be false. To gain a sensible assessment and forecast of the current situation is not possible through any logical analysis.

I think the two sides are way too far apart too strike any significant deal right now. The conservatives under Boris have two ideological goals with Brexit. One is Global Britain; the idea of more trade deals, less regulation, lower taxes, and more high-skilled immigration. The second is the Dominic Cummings-David Deutsch argument (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xdtssXITXuE) that outside of the EU Britain would have the flexibilty to adapt to changing circumstances, quicker error-correction, and more visible democratic institutions. The Theresa May style Brexit which focused entirely on the immigration argument, and doing as least economic damage as possible is no longer the strategy. Under the red-lines now being set by Macron of further hardlines on state-aid, competition, and taxes being tied to the EU, means that Boris cannot hit his aims. There isn't even room to compromise on this issue. Throw in the nationalistic and politically charged fisheries argument, means that Boris would be removed as leader if he accepted the deal. A mini deal that lessens the effects of No-deal Brexit is still possible however.

The definition of a Trade agreement is required to give a definitive answer. My opinion is that there are two possibilities and they are: a) (7% chance) - An all-embracing trade deal encompassing the full gamut of the relationships between the EU members and the UK (preferred by the EU) and b) (75%+ chance) - A skeletal or umbrella agreement under which lie a series of specific arrangements that refer to a particular subject and can be added to or deleted at a later stage (the preference of the UK). The UK government won the 2019 election with a determination to leave the EU, deal or no deal. The law was then passed to ensure there would be no extension to the transition period which ends 31st December 2020. An agreement in principle would have had to be completed by July 30, 2020 for presentation to the EU Parliament to meet the timetable. This date has passed. During the negotiations, 6 red lines have become apparent that both sides refuse to cross, and they are: 1) Fishing. The EU wish to keep the status quo in allowing their fishing industry to have unrestricted and unfettered access to UK sovereign territory. The UK is insisting on regaining control over its seas and suggesting a yearly negotiated quota system. 2) Level Playing Field. The EU is demanding that the UK is subjected to European standards after Brexit as in taxation, environment labour rights and state aid. The UK suggests this is not a consideration in any other trade agreement the EU has negotiated and is unacceptable and not conducive to an independent country and reserves the right to diverge. 3) The European Court of Justice. The EU is insisting that the ECJ is the sole arbiter of contract disputations that may occur. Not acceptable responds the UK as an independent party should be used. 4) Criminal Justice. The EU wants to retain the status quo by retaining the arrest warrant system. The UK disagrees. 5) Cultural Objects. With Elgin Marbles in mind compliments of Greece, the EU insists that all cultural objects be returned to their place of origin. The UK disagrees. 6) Financial Services. The EU insists that the City of London will lose its passport rights to operate in Europe. This is a major industry of the UK and as such is protected by the UK. The EU sees the UK as trying to ‚Äòcherry pick‚Äô the benefits of belonging to the EU while abrogating actual membership. The UK, after the Brexit referendum, European Election and General election sees it as listening to the will of the people and regaining its sovereignty as an independent country. Therefore, I propose a minimum chance of a comprehensive trade agreement being offered to the European Parliament by the Council of the European Union. It is contentious whether a skeletal umbrella agreement is necessary before 1st January 2021 that would be followed up by later deals, which I suggest is the probable outcome. Naturally, as this is a matter that will make or break the EU's entire survival, the EU would do anything it can to discourage more states from leaving the EU. Thus, while forcing a hard Brexit would hurt it economically, we would assume that the EU would need to hardline, as other nations who are skeptical of the EU would see how costly it would be to leave their experiment, and would be compelled to stay with the Union. Following the recent exit of the United Kingdom from the European Union, the next steps include securing a trade agreement to prevent a potential economic upset for the United Kingdom. The "Brexit" transition period is scheduled to end on 31 December 2020, though my prediction suggests only a 4% chance a trade agreement will be requested by that time. The process, from start to enactment, for trade deal traditionally takes several years and involves 30 stages. Prior to being presented to the EU Council of EU Parliament, the EU Commission must first prepare and negotiate the proposal. The process includes lengthy steps, such as public consultation, draft proposals, and consultation with the Trade Policy Committee. Though several agreements have been made by the UK with other non-EU nations, these deals were determined as the EU allowed the UK to transfer existing agreements. Of the agreements completed since 2018, the amount only covers 8% of total UK trade. Additionally, relations between UK and EU leadership does not appear on good terms, with both sides expressing tough words to the media. Despite the obstacles, the UK has several incentives to ensure the process is initiated in a timely manner. A new trade agreement will help stop new tariffs coming into force after 31 December 2020. Seven of the top ten trading partners of the UK are in EU members. The failure to produce an agreement would leave the UK under WTO rules, applying tariffs on most goods, causing prices in the EU to skyrocket, and making products more difficult to sell. Based on the amount of time needed and conflict between leadership, only a 4% chance exists of a concluded agreement by 1 January 2021.

Even as 49% of the UK's trade is with the EU, it still runs a deficit, primarily as a result of goods with Germany and the Netherlands. The economic impact to the EU members with which the UK has a goods deficit could be the shock that triggers economic uncertainty for long period. While I suspect that the majority of UK exports to the EU could be shifted to EU members, the key industries such as parama and petroleum products would put the EU at a disadvantage. The UK government has the blueprint of the Canada-Free Trade Agreement as well as the experience of having secured 40 trade deals, by leveraging strengths and presumably accepting restrictions on agriculture based goods (it will be spun as more for the UK), it seems probable that the UK could have an agreement that would be politically viable within the UK by the end of the year. Furthermore, in order to minimize the economic impact to the EU and sustain the ability of the EU to serve a function for its members, it too will give a little to have something by the end of the year. Finally, I suspect that not everything will be settled, but sufficient agreement will be made to agree to postpone the rougher spots until after the New Year.
